# TypeScript Opinions

## Architecture
- Feature-folder organisation; one module per feature, not one barrel of utils.
- `src/` for source; `tests/` mirrors the `src/` structure.
- One module per file; the file name matches the primary export name in `kebab-case`.
- Prefer named exports — no default exports.

## Naming
- Types, interfaces, enums, classes: `PascalCase`.
- Variables, functions, parameters: `camelCase`.
- Module-level primitive constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`.
- File names: `kebab-case.ts`.
- No `I` prefix on interfaces — use descriptive names.

## Formatting
- 2-space indent. Spaces, not tabs.
- Single quotes for strings; template literals only when interpolating.
- Trailing commas in multi-line arrays, objects, and parameter lists (`"trailingComma": "all"` in Prettier).
- Semicolons required.
- Max line length: 100 characters.

## TypeScript Patterns
- `strict: true` in `tsconfig.json` — no exceptions.
- Prefer `unknown` over `any`; never use `any` without an inline comment explaining why it is safe.
- Use `import type` for type-only imports.
- Use `satisfies` to validate object shape without widening the inferred type.
- Prefer `readonly` arrays and properties for data that must not mutate.
- Use discriminated unions over class hierarchies for modelling state.

## Async
- Prefer `async`/`await` over `.then()` chains.
- Always `await` promises — never fire-and-forget without explicit handling.
- Propagate errors with `throw`; catch only at boundaries (top-level handlers, API routes).

## No-Go Zone
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.
- No default exports — named exports only.
- No `!` non-null assertion — use optional chaining or type guards.
- No `// @ts-ignore` — fix the type error.
- No `require()` — use ES module `import`.
- No mutable module-level state.
